Step 1: Create a GitHub Account
	Go to GitHub.
	Click on "Sign up" and follow the instructions to create an account.
Step 2: Install Git
	Download and install Git from git-scm.com.
	Follow the installation instructions for your operating system.
Step 3: Configure Git
	Open your terminal or command prompt.
	Set your username and email:

		git config --global user.name "Your Name"
		git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"

Step 4: Create a New Repository on GitHub
	Log in to your GitHub account.
	Click the "+" icon in the top-right corner and select "New repository".
	Fill in the repository name, description, and choose the visibility (public or private).
	Click "Create repository".
Step 5: Initialize a Local Repository
	Open your terminal or command prompt.
	Navigate to the directory where you want to store your Python code:

		cd path/to/your/project

	Initialize a new Git repository:
		
		git init

Step 6: Add Your Python Files
	Create or move your Python files into the project directory.
	Add the files to the staging area:
	
		git add .

Step 7: Commit Your Changes
	Commit the files with a descriptive message:

	git commit -m "Initial commit"

Step 8: Connect to Your GitHub Repository
	Copy the repository URL from your GitHub repository page.
	Add the remote repository:

	git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repository.git

Step 9: Push Your Code to GitHub
	Push your local repository to GitHub:

	git push -u origin master

Step 10: Verify Your Code on GitHub
	Go to your GitHub repository page.
	You should see your Python files listed there.

Additional Tips
	Branching: Create branches for new features or bug fixes.

	git checkout -b feature-branch

	Pull Requests: Use pull requests to merge branches and collaborate with others.
	Cloning: Clone existing repositories to your local machine.

	git clone https://github.com/your-username/your-repository.git
